rmk:
On migration.  High-pitch call, and then flew away.
(Somewhat overlapped by operation noise).
May not be the same individual as in XC432422.

[Later note]:
Originally uploaded as Phylloscopus borealoides.
I noticed that the frequency (6 kHz) was higher than that of typical
call of Phylloscopus borealoides, and more resembled
that of Phylloscopus tenellipes.
In the literature, Phylloscopus borealoides is reported to
issue similarly high-pitched notes (particularly in excited state).
The state was probably not particularly excited.  I heard
only one note (of the same pitch) before this recording.
The voice was from a high coniferous tree,
and then flew away.  There was no indication of a rapid
sequence of repetitive notes as is frequent in excited state.
The location where I recorded XC432422 was some hundreds
meters different.  I changed the ID to the more likely one
(as judged from the frequency)  to call attention.
The location is very approximate.
